The influence of pragmatism on institutionalism and the role of
rules and habits in decision-making1, whether by Thorstein Veblen (1990; 1970; 1946) or John Commons (1934; 
1950), has been debated for about twenty years (Bush1993;
Kilpinen1998; Milberg2001; Mirowski2005; Hodgson2004; 
2006; Gronow 2008). This literature has largely highlighted the 
filiation between habits in William James (1931a; 1931b; 
1956) and this movement of economic theory (Twomey 1998; 
Hodgson 2003; Lawlor 2005; Barbalet 2008). Pratten (2015) has 
extended the analysis by focusing on the thought of John Dewey. This focus on habits has however left aside the role 
of emotions in this school of thought.
